"katsaros_liritzis_laskaris_2010.T124253" [label=<<b>THESIS</b><br/>Katsaros-T., Liritzis-Ioannis, Laskaris-N.<br/>p. 71<br/><i>We reproduced in laboratory the white powder<br/>sample PSI-1 (which is composed of cerussite and<br/>hydrocerussite, and is therefore lead white)<br/>following Theophrastus's recipe (on the<br/>preparation of lead white): .We cut commercial<br/>metallic lead in the shape of a brick {approx. 10<br/>cm length by 5 cm width by 2 cm thickness}, .We<br/>placed vinegar on the bottom of a ceramic vessel,<br/>.We hung the brick-shaped piece of lead over the<br/>vinegar within the ceramic vessel, .We covered the<br/>vessel with a skin {approx. 1 mm (in thickness)}<br/>quasi-transparent to air (i.e., such that it<br/>breathes), .We placed the vessel under the sun,<br/>.We waited {for 10 days}, {at temperatures of<br/>average 30 °C and a range of 27-55 degrees}, .We<br/>removed the skin cover, .We took the brick-shaped<br/>lead out, .We removed the white powdered layer<br/>(thus formed) on the surface of the lead by<br/>scratching, .In a marble mortar, we washed and<br/>ground down to a fine powder the white powdered<br/>layer using a marble pestle, .We waited for it to<br/>dry out under the sun, ( .We obtained the white<br/>powder sample PSI-1 (which is composed of<br/>cerussite and hydrocerussite, and is therefore<br/>lead white) following Theophrastus's recipe (on<br/>the preparation of lead white) ), .We applied it<br/>on a prepared wooden surface with a gypsum OR<br/>calcite support<br/></i><font point-size="12">"Sample PSI- 1 ... calcite support"</font>>, gephi_label="THES", locus="p. 71", speaker="Katsaros-T., Liritzis-Ioannis, Laskaris-N.", text="Sample PSI- 1 is the reproduced in laboratory white pow- der following Theophrastus ancient recipe On Stones. (ref. On Stones§ 56 above) . Ccommercial metallic lead cut in the shape of a brick approx. 10 cm length by 5 cm width and 2 cm thickness, hanged over within a ceramic ... out. A white powdered layer on its surface was removed by scratch, then washed in a marble mortar and ground down with marble pestle to a fine powder, following a dry out under the sun. Subsequently it was applied on a prepared wooden surface with a gypsum or calcite support", paraphrasis="We reproduced in laboratory the white powder sample PSI-1 (which is composed of cerussite and hydrocerussite, and is therefore lead white) following Theophrastus's recipe (on the preparation of lead white): .We cut commercial metallic lead in the shape of a brick {approx. 10 cm length by 5 cm width by 2 cm thickness}, .We placed vinegar on the bottom of a ceramic vessel, .We hung the brick-shaped piece of lead over the vinegar within the ceramic vessel, .We covered the vessel with a skin {approx. 1 mm (in thickness)} quasi-transparent to air (i.e., such that it breathes), .We placed the vessel under the sun, .We waited {for 10 days}, {at temperatures of average 30 °C and a range of 27-55 degrees}, .We removed the skin cover, .We took the brick-shaped lead out, .We removed the white powdered layer (thus formed) on the surface of the lead by scratching, .In a marble mortar, we washed and ground down to a fine powder the white powdered layer using a marble pestle, .We waited for it to dry out under the sun, ( .We obtained the white powder sample PSI-1 (which is composed of cerussite and hydrocerussite, and is therefore lead white) following Theophrastus's recipe (on the preparation of lead white) ), .We applied it on a prepared wooden surface with a gypsum OR calcite support ", manifestation="explicit", source="katsaros_liritzis_laskaris_2010", fillcolor="#f0faf0", color="#82b366", style="rounded,filled", shape="box", margin="0.30,0.1"];

